==Trivia==
*Hogan's role of training [[Tony Stark]] in boxing during ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' is a nod to his background as a former professional boxer in the comics, which is also how he earned his nickname because of his refusal to fight back.
*Hogan's look and attire in the flashbacks shown in ''[[Iron Man 3]]'' and in a news footage picture depicted in ''[[Spider-Man: No Way Home]]'' are an homage to the character of Vincent Vega, played by [[John Travolta]] in the movie ''{{WPS|Pulp Fiction}}''.
*[[Jon Favreau]] personally chose the scene from ''{{WPS|Downton Abbey}}'' Hogan wakes up to in ''[[Iron Man 3]]''.<ref>[https://twitter.com/Jon_Favreau/status/328581485173043201 Jon Favreau on Twitter - April 28, 2013]</ref>
*In ''[[Spider-Man: No Way Home]]'', Hogan is revealed to have sleep apnea and uses a CPAP machine to treat this.

==Behind the Scenes==
*In early storyboards of ''[[Iron Man 3]]'', Happy Hogan was originally supposed to die in the [[Destruction of the Chinese Theatre|explosion]] caused by [[Jack Taggart]], but the idea was scrapped.<ref>[https://www.comicbookmovie.com/iron_man/iron_man_3/iron-man-3-happy-hogan-jon-favreau-was-supposed-to-die-a109394 IRON MAN 3: Happy Hogan (Jon Favreau) Was Supposed To Die!]</ref>
*[[David Rowden]] and [[Richard Verran Townsend]] were stunt doubles for [[Jon Favreau]] in the role of Happy Hogan.
*[[Jeff Ridgway]], [[James Payton]] and [[Derek Sulek]] were stand-ins for [[Jon Favreau]] in the role of Happy Hogan.

